    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-06T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-06T06:00:00-05:00" n="951"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d951">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/6–654: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé at Saigon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MR2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McClintock</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-06T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >June 6, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2686. Repeated information Paris 953, Geneva 202. <persName corresp="#p_DM1"
                        >DeJean</persName> told me this afternoon <persName corresp="#p_SGR1"
                        >General Salan</persName> departs Paris tonight with <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>, apparently to assume command ground forces
                    Indochina under <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>’s overall
                        direction.<note n="1" xml:id="d951fn1">On June 3, <persName
                            corresp="#p_EGP1">Gen. Paul Ely</persName> was appointed Commissioner
                        General and Commander in Chief in Indochina. <persName corresp="#p_SGR1"
                            >Gen. Raoul Salan</persName> was named his military deputy. In telegram
                        2676 from Saigon, June 6, <persName corresp="#p_MR2">McClintock</persName>
                        states that the “removal of <persName corresp="#p_DM1">Dejean</persName> is
                        a serious blow to furtherance of US policy in Indochina. Not only has he
                        been the most courageous French official here, but also the only one with a
                        clear-eyed view of what stakes we are fighting for, not only in Southeast
                        Asia but likewise in Europe against international communism. … In view of
                        our vested interest in this war, I believe that Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> has a right to indicate our concern
                        that <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> be given top-notch political
                        advisors.” (751G.00/6–654) In telegram <gloss target="#t_Dulte1"
                            >Dulte</gloss> 158 from Geneva, June 7, Under Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGWB1">Smith</persName> concurred in <persName
                            corresp="#p_MR2">McClintock</persName>’s estimate of <persName
                            corresp="#p_DM1">Dejean</persName>’s removal. (751G.00/6–754)</note>
                </p>
                <p>This news strikes me much as did announcement that two cruisers <hi rend="italic"
                        >Cloire</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Montcalm</hi> are now enroute Far Eastern
                    station. These six-inch-gun ships can only be utilized in final phase of
                    evacuation Haiphong perimeter: namely, to guard withdrawal from Do Son
                    beachhead.</p>
                <p>Similarly, it is my conjecture that <persName corresp="#p_SGR1">Salan</persName>,
                    because of his extensive knowledge of Indochina, is being sent here not in any
                    hope of conducting an offensive military campaign but to use his expertise in
                    the administration of an armistice.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MR2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McClintock</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
